<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Leg 5 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figure 14. Heteranthessius unisetatus sp. nov., male A maxilliped B leg 1 C leg 2 D endopod of left leg 3 E leg 4 F endopod of right leg 4 G leg 5. Scale bars: 0.05 mm (A-F); 0.02 mm (G)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1115.83266.figure14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/720734" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">14G</figureCitation>
) represented by small papilla tipped with one pinnate seta 47 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
long. Leg 6 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. Heteranthessius unisetatus sp. nov., male A habitus, dorsal B urosome, ventral C rostrum D antennule E antenna F labrum G mandible H maxillule I maxilla. Scale bars: 0.2 mm (A); 0.1 mm (B, C); 0.05 mm (D, E); 0.02 mm (F-I)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1115.83266.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/720733" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">13B</figureCitation>
) represented by two small setae on genital operculum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">The specific name of the new species is derived from Latin words, referring to the presence of a single seta on the maxillule and maxilla.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The genus 
<taxonomicName class="Hexanauplia" family="Lichomolgidae" genus="Heteranthessius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heteranthessius" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Heteranthessius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
consists of four known species: 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. dubius" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="dubius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">H. dubius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(T. Scott, 1903) from an unknown host in Scotland (T. 
<bibRefCitation author="Scott, T" journalOrPublisher="Twenty-first Annual Report of the Fishery Board for Scotland" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="109 - 135" refId="B51" refString="Scott, T, 1903. On some new and rare Crustacea collected at various times in connection with the investigations of the Fisheries board for Scotland. Twenty-first Annual Report of the Fishery Board for Scotland 21 (3): 109 - 135" title="On some new and rare Crustacea collected at various times in connection with the investigations of the Fisheries board for Scotland." volume="21" year="1903">Scott 1903</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. scotti" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="scotti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">H. scotti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bocquet, Stock &amp; Bernard, 1959 from calcareous algae at Roscoff, France (
<bibRefCitation author="Bocquet, C" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Koninklijke Nederlande Akademie van Wetenschappen series c" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="111 - 118" refId="B2" refString="Bocquet, C, Stock, JH, Bernard, F, 1959. Copepodes parasites d'invertebres des cotes de France. IX. Description d'une nouvelle espece remarquable de Lichomolgidae. Heteranthessius scotti n. sp. (Cyclopoida). Proceedings of the Koninklijke Nederlande Akademie van Wetenschappen series c 62 (2): 111 - 118" title="Copepodes parasites d'invertebres des cotes de France. IX. Description d'une nouvelle espece remarquable de Lichomolgidae. Heteranthessius scotti n. sp. (Cyclopoida)." volume="62" year="1959">Bocquet et al. 1959</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. furcatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="furcatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">H. furcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Stock, 1971 from a tunicate in the Mediterranean Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Stock, JH" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin de la Societe Zoologique de France" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="335 - 340" refId="B55" refString="Stock, JH, 1971. Decouverte du genre Heteranthessius (Copepoda) on Mediterranee: H. furcatus n. sp. Bulletin de la Societe Zoologique de France 95: 335 - 340" title="Decouverte du genre Heteranthessius (Copepoda) on Mediterranee: H. furcatus n. sp." volume="95" year="1971">Stock 1971</bibRefCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. hoi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="hoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">H. hoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="López-González">Lopez-Gonzalez</normalizedToken>
&amp; Conradi, 1995 from an actiniarian at Gibraltar (
<bibRefCitation author="Lopez-Gonzalez, PJ" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="107 - 116" refId="B39" refString="Lopez-Gonzalez, PJ, Conradi, M, 1995. Heteranthessius hoi, a new species (Copepoda: Pseudanthessiidae) from a sea-anemone in the Straits of Gibraltar, with remarks on the genus. Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington 108 (1): 107 - 116" title="Heteranthessius hoi, a new species (Copepoda: Pseudanthessiidae) from a sea-anemone in the Straits of Gibraltar, with remarks on the genus." volume="108" year="1995">
<normalizedToken originalValue="López-González">Lopez-Gonzalez</normalizedToken>
and Conradi 1995
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lee &amp; Chang &amp; Kim" authorityYear="2022" class="Hexanauplia" family="Lichomolgidae" genus="Heteranthessius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heteranthessius unisetatus" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unisetatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Heteranthessius unisetatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. is easily distinguishable from the congeners by its unique morphological features: the maxillule bears only a single seta apically, against two setae in the four congeners, the maxilla is unsegmented, with a single seta apically, against two-segmented, with one spine or spiniform process and one seta on the distal segment in the congeners, and leg 5 is represented by a single seta, against two setae in the congeners. The most striking feature of the new species is the possession of two inner setae on the second endopodal segment of leg 1. Because the latter feature is very extraordinary and we have failed to find the same armature condition in other poecilostome copepods, it may be interpreted as an abnormality. However, it is remarkable that both left and right leg 1 display the same setation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
